annotations: I’ve had enough

She is tired of working so hard for no reason, for something she can’t even fully know is supportive of her, and having the same thing being the only reason she’s still doing it. She needs something to tell her that she’s alive but it does not seem enough.

Something inside me
 Forgets that I’m alive

With her co-dependency on needing something to support her, something to work for, the speaker forgets she is still a breathing person. That this work she’s been doing has been so meaningless, her life does not seem genuine enough to remind her.

I don’t know what I’m working for
 Tell me I’m doing alright

Despite doubting them, the speaker still wants validation, a push to work and to be complimented for it. It’s because she has no direction still, so she needs the only thing left in her life to say something. At this point, the ‘you’ figure could be music, work, an actual person, or etc.

It’s your faults they can’t see
 But don’t think I wouldn’t notice

Again, with the theme of finding flaws inside this ‘you’ figure for whatever reason. The speaker still is not ready for forgiveness, to move on, or to do things independently after past events. She would of course notice the ‘you’ figure’s faults, it’s the only thing she focuses on now, rather than herself.

Unless the truth
 Comes spilling out of
 The dark you breathe in

The ‘you’ figure is not perfect, in fact, they may even doubt the speaker’s success despite being a support system. But having this figure or motivation can come crumbling down if the support is a lie. The speaker may also be insecure and always want to find flaws in whatever is holding them up because they’re the only reason she is doing anything.
I don’t want to be forgiven

The speaker does not want to be forgiven for whatever sins they committed, whether it was their own fault or something unrelated. It may be because they’re moving on from a failure or don’t know how to go past it.

annotations:
Small town quiet, I could live it
 If you could live too
their lover left the town. the speaker thinks they can live there, but not without them.

If you’re alone
 What am I?
the comparison of their lover being alone, by whatever “alone” means for them, and the speaker’s state (left behind), shows a large contrast between “aloneness.”

And your hair still swirls around me
 And your legs are crossed inside me

the memories of their lover’s hair and legs are perhaps metaphors for still missing their physical attributes. “legs are crossed” may allude to a sexual meaning, or not all; it’s the overall feeling missed.

annotations: I know I haven’t moved at all

Despite moving near this person, the speaker knows they haven’t moved internally. They have not moved on because they’re still scratching at the surface, clawing for this person to still be willingly involved in their life. They know they have not advanced past them and not changed as a person at all. This is because they’re making the person a part of them.
